<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / International Company News: Japanese cement groups to merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S biggest and sixth-largest cement-makers are to merged next year. The
link-up is designed to create economies of scale in the face of weak demand
and competition from cheap imports.
Onoda Cement, the leading producer, and part of the Mitsui Group of
industrial companies, will merge next October with Chichibu Cement. They
will form a group, to be called Chichibu Onoda, with annual capacity of
17.94m tonnes, nearly a quarter of Japan's annual demand of 80m tonnes.
At yesterday's closing price in Tokyo, Onoda was capitalised at Y241.8bn
(Dollars 2.25bn) and Chichibu at Y65bn.
The merger will allow them to cut distribution costs by Y300m in the first
year, to March 1995. This will double, to Y600m, savings in the following
year, said Mr Takaharu Unno, Onoda's senior managing director. Annual sales
of the merged group will be an estimated Y264.5bn in the first year, on
which taxable profits are forecast at Y8.2bn.
The pair also plans to shed an unspecified number of workers over the next
three years through natural attrition, said Mr Takahashi Kurihara, president
of Chichibu.
The merger could be the first step in a welcome restructuring of the cement
industry, said Mr Masaya Fujimura, head of the cement association of Japan.
Japanese cement demand has dropped 38 per cent over the past decade, from
130m tonnes annually. The government's attempts to boost public works
through three spending packages over the past 18 months have had little
effect, said company executives.
They blamed this on a drop in office construction, and local government
caution over letting new contracts, in the wake of a wave of arrests of
construction industry executives and public officials. On top of this, there
is stiff competition from cement imported from South Korea, which has become
increasingly cheap as the yen has risen in value.
The pressures on the industry were underlined yesterday when Onoda announced
a 31.5 per cent drop in pre-tax profits, to Y1.76bn in the first six months
to September, from Y2.57bn last time. Sales fell 6.5 per cent to Y105.3bn.
Onoda warned that turnover would fall by the same percentage, to Y218.7bn
for the full year to next March, the first sales setback for seven years.
Pre-tax profits are set to fall by 40.6 per cent to Y5.3bn.
The merger will by undertaken on an equal share exchange, at a rate of 2.1
Onoda shares for one Chichibu share.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Onoda Cement.
    Chichibu Cement.
    Chichibu Onoda.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3241 Cement, Hydraulic.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Mergers &amp; acquisitions.
    PEOP  Labour.
</TP>
