<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / International Company News: Exchange watchdog called into
Murdoch share row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL fund managers yesterday sought to involve the Australian
Securities Commission in the heated debate over differential voting rights.
Mr Rupert Murdoch sparked the debate with his desire to introduce a new
class of 'super shares', with multiple voting rights, at News Corporation,
the media, film and publishing group.
At present, share structures incorporating differential voting rights do not
feature on the Australian Stock Exchange (ASX). The exchange is already
considering whether it should change its listing rules to permit these in
the wake of News Corp's proposal.
Yesterday, the Australian Investment Managers' Group (AIMG) - which
represents most of the large institutional shareholders - said it saw
implications for the takeover provisions written into corporate law. It
'would encourage the ASC to explore' these, it said.
After a meeting of members, the AIMG formally expressed 'overwhelming
support' for the principle of one share, one vote, and 'strong opposition to
any proposal that effectively allows a major shareholder to gain and pass
control of a corporation without paying a market premium'.
There are fears in this case that, because the super shares would lose their
multiple voting advantage if they were sold, the Murdoch family interest
would enjoy 'creeping control' of News Corp over time. Mr Murdoch currently
controls - directly or through Cruden Investments, the family company -
almost 33 per cent of News' equity.
Mr Peter Griffin, chairman of the AIMG and vice-chairman of Rothschild
Australia Asset Management, said the fund managers were concerned that the
introduction of differential voting rights would be 'extraordinarily
detrimental to the image of the Australian capital markets'.
If control of corporations became concentrated in the hands of minority
share-holders, Australian companies could also be 'severely constrained in
their ability to tap international and domestic capital markets'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>News Corp.
</CO>
