<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Oxford Instruments improves 19% to Pounds
5.1m as orders show recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OXFORD INSTRUMENTS, the advanced instrumentation group, reported a 19 per
cent increase in interim pre-tax profits yesterday and said the rate of new
orders was showing 'strong signs of recovery'.
Pre-tax profits grew from Pounds 4.26m to Pounds 5.07m in the six months to
September 26. Earnings per share increased by 12 per cent to 6.6p (5.9p) and
the interim dividend is being increased by 7 per cent to 1.5p (1.4p). The
shares closed up 8p at 296p.
The profit improvement was underpinned by an 8 per cent increase in
turnover. This grew to Pounds 48.6m (Pounds 45.1m) buoyed by new orders,
which Mr Peter Williams, chairman and chief executive, said were up 10 per
cent from the start of the year.
With 85 per cent of sales outside the UK, Mr Martin Lamaison, finance
director, said the group mainly used sterling's devaluation to improve its
competitiveness and boost sales volumes rather than to enhance margins.
Operating profits jumped to Pounds 1.9m (Pounds 797,000) more than
offsetting a decline in interest income to Pounds 359,000 (Pounds 500,000),
mainly reflecting the group's lower mid-year cash balances of Pounds 2.6m,
down from Pounds 6.7m at the start of the year.
The Pounds 4.1m decline in cash balances represented an increase in working
capital, reflecting the stronger order book and progress with long-term
contracts and the group's second Dollars 25m (Pounds 16.5m) synchrotron
machine.
Despite earlier concerns over the impact of uncertainties in the US
healthcare market, Mr Williams said sales and profits from its magnetic
resonance imaging (MRI) joint venture with Siemens held up well. Oxford's
share of income from the joint venture slipped slightly to Pounds 2.81m
(Pounds 2.96m).
</TEXT>
