<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Lloyd's trusts approach limit of capacity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO MORE Lloyd's investment trusts were launched yesterday amid further
indications that the limit of institutional investor interest in the new
Lloyd's schemes is being reached.
Angerstein Underwriting Trust, an investment trust sponsored by NatWest
Markets and Stace Barr, the Lloyd's agency, announced that it aimed to raise
Pounds 75m through a placement and offer for subscription, while a smaller
vehicle, Corporate Membership, also issued its prospectus.
Corporate Membership, formed by individual members of Lloyd's and sponsored
by Peel, Hunt, the stockbrokers, is seeking to raise Pounds 20m through an
offer for subscription.
However, SG Warburg and Chartwell, which planned to raise between Pounds
100m and Pounds 150m for New London Capital, are understood to be planning
to scale back their fund to between Pounds 75m and Pounds 85m.
At Angerstein, Mr Charles Phillips of NatWest Markets said Pounds 67.5m had
been placed with institutions, although it was aiming to raise Pounds 23m
from retail investors.
Angerstein will provide Pounds 111m of capacity on syndicates recommended by
Stace Barr, its independent Lloyd's adviser. Corporate Membership said it
had secured in excess of Pounds 16m of secured capacity from syndicates and
had identified a further Pounds 15m of syndicate capacity.
