<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Royal Doulton promises 3p dividend after
demerger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Doulton, the fine china company, yesterday announced that it intended
to pay a dividend of 3p to shareholders after its demerger from its parent,
Pearson, publishers of the Financial Times.
The group made the announcement in its listing particulars document,
published after some initial difficulties late yesterday. The particulars
stated that on a pro forma basis, Royal Doulton would have paid a notional
full-year dividend of 6.6p.
The document also warned shareholders not to expect a robust performance
from Royal Doulton in 1993 as profits would be hit by redundancy costs and
short-time working.
Pearson will offer 54.9m Royal Doulton shares on a one-for-10 basis. A rough
guide to the price at which Royal Doulton may start trading on December 2
can be found in a listings footnote. Pearson has agreed to buy from Royal
Doulton shares at 244p, if necessary. This is likely to occur only if
Pearson issues more of its own shares before then.
On a pro forma basis, Royal Doulton has net debt of Pounds 39.5m. Gearing,
normally high at this time, is 38 per cent.
The particulars also state that Royal Doulton's first-half results - which
show a deficit of Pounds 3.8m - include a Pounds 2m exceptional charge for
losses on the sale of the Canadian Financial Post newspaper group to another
Pearson company. Pearson last year transferred the Post into Royal Doulton
Canada for tax reasons.
The demerger got off to a shaky start yesterday as the stock exchange
recalled early copies of the particulars.
It is believed that the document contained errors over holdings in Royal
Doulton which Lazard Investors and associated companies of Lazard Freres
will have after the demerger. Lazard Brothers is sponsoring Royal Doulton's
introduction to the official list. Pearson has a stake in the Lazard
investment banking group.
Some 25 to 30 incorrect copies of the document were collected from analysts
who had attended a meeting.
Meanwhile, Pearson said its third-quarter pre-tax profits rose from Pounds
61.7m to Pounds 100.6m. The shares rose by 16p on the news to 574p.
</TEXT>
