<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / UK business chiefs want single currency, CBI survey suggests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW row over Britain's position in Europe was brewing last night after an
authoritative business survey suggested many of the country's top
industrialists back sterling's participation in a single European currency.
The survey, which is due to be unveiled this weekend by the Confederation of
British Industry, showed that a large proportion of its senior members
continued to think that Europe would be the focal point of British trade and
investment in the future.
The CBI last night refused to reveal precise details of the survey but its
director-general, Mr Howard Davies, signalled that the results would be a
key topic of debate at the organisation's conference next week by strongly
attacking the attitude of the British government towards the EU.
'We are rather nervous about the way the debate in the Conservative party
has moved, such that it is almost impossible to talk about it,' he said in
an interview with The Guardian newspaper. 'What some of our big members are
anxious about is the notion of a single currency on the other side of the
Channel and Ukrainian coupons over here.'
Mr Davies added that the issue of Europe could not be buried and it would be
a dangerous mistake for the government to close off the option of moving to
a single currency. 'It's all very well to say we've had a competitive
devaluation, we are offshore, we are in the single market and we have
incredibly cheap labour costs,' he said.
'But it doesn't seem like a credible long term strategy. We are not
comfortable about being on the sidelines and ridiculing the whole notion.
You only have to go across the Channel to see they take it rather
seriously.' CBI officials said last night the survey results underlined that
Britain's businesses were clearly at odds with the government on the future
of Europe - and that the demise of the European exchange rate mechanism
should not preclude attempts to move ahead towards European monetary union.
They said the survey had taken the form of telephone interviews with 200
chief executives of leading British firms, and they would be treating its
results as an important contribution to the debate on Europe.
'CBI members favour currency stability and that is why they are in favour of
a single currency,' a CBI spokesman commented last night. 'They would not be
happy for Britain to be an offshore island linked to the community, with
other members participating in a single currency.'
Clarke faces lobbying, Page 10
</TEXT>
