<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Observer: Grant status
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Want Wall Street cred? Then leave a copy of Grant's Interest Rate Observer
lying about the office.
Jim Grant's fortnightly newsletter, celebrating its tenth birthday with a
fat tome of past apercus, is required reading for anyone seeking a quirky,
contrarian view of the financial world and those who inhabit it.
Laced, unusually for American writing, with a rich sense of irony, Grant's
is written by the originator of the Current Yield column on Barron's, the US
financial weekly. When Grant went solo, Jim Rogers, George Soros's former
partner, was his first subscriber.
While his wife beavered away at Lehman Kuhn Loeb, Grant got established by
noisily deploring just the sort of deals she was doing. He fingered Olympia
&amp; York early on, rechristening its Canary Wharf site 'London's own North
Dakota'.
But Grant has not always been right. He admits that his greatest predictive
gaff was to fail to see the 'levitation of stocks and bonds in the last
couple of years'. No surprise then that he thinks financial assets are
hopelessly over-priced and commodities dirt cheap. Hence his motto for the
Clinton years: 'Down with paper. Up with things'.
</TEXT>
