<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Not so long ago motor racing was widely seen as a noisy and dangerous
pastime (scarcely a sport) for the sort of overgrown boy who went 'vroom,
vroom' under his breath when a car with a broken silencer went down the
road. Now it is part of the global hype which sells everything from cameras
to condoms. The Team (BBC2, 9.30) is a seven-part series about McLaren and
their efforts to recapture the Formula One World Championship.
In last week's news quiz, Have I Got News For You (BBC2, 10.00), Paul
Merton, the quickest and most dead-pan of the contestants, ridiculed
question master Angus Deayton for the complexity of his carefully prepared
'funny' answers. He has a point. Deayton is becoming more verbose and less
funny as his contributions expand. Time to forego the autocue and push
Deayton back on his own resources.
It is hard to know when the daily 'documentary soap' Sarajevo - A Street
Under Siege will be on air since it lasts only two minutes and is tacked on
the end of programmes, but you should catch it on BBC2 at 10.25.
</TEXT>
