<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Chinese trainee airline pilots arrive in Oxford
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ADRIAN MICHAELS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST GROUP of Chinese trainee airline pilots to go abroad has arrived
at the Oxford Air Training School, Adrian Michaels writes.
This follows September's announcement that the Chinese Civil Aviation
Authority had awarded its first overseas civilian cadet training contract to
the school.
The pilots, all of whom are on their first trip outside China, will be put
on a 56-week course costing Pounds 55,000 each which will qualify them for a
full British commercial pilot's licence and instrument rating.
They are then due to return to China for further training.
The school sees their arrival as an acknowledgement by China that it has a
fast-growing civil aviation sector but is short of pilots and lacks access
to the latest technology.
The school said: 'Their English is excellent and so far they have taken to
the change in circumstances very well.'
The trainees will spend their first four weeks in the classroom at the
school, which said it had trained 10,000 from 40 countries since it was
founded in 1962.
They will be living in Oxford with a group of nearly 200 other trainees from
18 countries.
