<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Rule clash may force tendering change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CLASH between two European directives could force a revision of government
policy on compulsory competitive tendering by councils.
Many authorities now advertise contracts on the basis that Transfer of
Undertakings (Protection of Employment) regulations of 1981, known as Tupe,
will apply. In effect these require any bidder to maintain the same
workforce on the same wages and conditions of service.
The European Commission believes, however, that this might clash with the
procurement directive, which forbids authorities from forcing bidders to use
local labour forces.
According to today's Local Government Chronicle the commission raised the
issue after it saw an advertisement in the Official Journal of the European
Communities tendering Croydon borough council's financial services work.
The advertisement stated that the council's existing staff must be
transferred to the bidder. Croydon confirmed that the commission had queried
the advertisement.
Mr Cliff Davis-Coleman, of Clause 26, a lobby group for contractors, said
the commission's stance could sweep away the serious obstacle Tupe poses to
private contractors. He said: 'If the commission insists that this is indeed
a local labour clause then the environment department will have to amend its
advice for the Next Steps initiative and for compulsory competitive
tendering.'
Separately, Britain's biggest local authority is facing a claim that it
awarded contracts worth Pounds 22m uncompetitively.
Strathclyde Regional Council, centred on Glasgow, told potential bidders for
its cleaning contracts that Tupe applied. The contracts were won by the
in-house teams.
But the Business Services Association, another lobby group of contractors,
branded the policy anti-competitive in a letter to Mr Allan Stewart, the
Scottish office minister.
</TEXT>
