FT  12 NOV 93 / Sinn Fein leader is barred from US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton has barred the latest attempt by Mr Gerry Adams, the
Sinn Fein leader, to enter the US. The exclusion was made because of Mr
Adams' alleged involvement with the IRA.
The White House yesterday confirmed the decision had been taken even though
Mr Adams' declared reason for his trip was to explain his peace initiative
with Mr John Hume, the leader of Northern Ireland's Social Democratic and
Labour Party.
In a letter to New York's departing Democrat mayor Mr David Dinkins, which
was published in yesterday's Irish Times, Mr Clinton said: 'Credible
evidence exists that Adams remains involved at the highest level devising
IRA strategy. . . (he) has still not publicly renounced terrorism.'
A US official said Mr Clinton had pledged during his election campaign to
consider granting Mr Adams a visa. He added: 'We did consider it, and we
decided against it.'
Mr Dinkins' office said it believed a visit by Mr Adams would help the peace
process.
Mr Adams yesterday said the remarks by Mr Clinton were 'black propaganda'
based on 'lies concocted by the British'.
He insisted he had no involvement in terrorism and added: 'This type of
unfounded allegation is used by the British government as a cover for its
real intention, which is to prevent any informed debate about its
involvement in Irish affairs.'
