<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Carey warns on Church finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHURCH of England faces 'serious but not disastrous' financial problems
as a result of an alarming decline in its assets, Dr George Carey,
Archbishop of Canterbury, told its General Synod yesterday.
'We have been living beyond our means for many years,' the archbishop told a
debate on a report into the conduct of the Church commissioners, who are
responsible for the Church's investments. He said action had to be taken to
ensure that the problems did not become unmanageable.
The total value of the commissioners' income-producing assets declined from
nearly Pounds 3bn in 1989 to Pounds 2.16bn last year, largely due to falls
in the property market. In August a report from the accountants Coopers &amp;
Lybrand commissioned by Dr Carey criticised the commissioners' heavy
speculation in property.
The Rt Rev John Wayne, Bishop of Chelmsford, who chaired the Lambeth Group -
a committee set up to consider the report - told the Synod he did not seek
to 'minimise the seriousness of the situation or to make light of the errors
of judgment, or the instances of organisational weakness' which
investigations had revealed. The Church commissioners, he said, saw
yesterday's debate as an occasion for them to offer a public apology for
what had happened.
There had, said the bishop, been three principal problems:
The commissioners increased an already large exposure to property, and
compounded the problem by borrowing to finance speculative property
investments.
Their assets committee failed to receive regular and accurate reports from
executive management.
The commissioners took on commitments to finance clergy benefits in excess
of their financial capacity.
As a result of the fall in investment income parishes will have to meet more
of their costs - a 15 per cent rise in local financial support is being
sought - and the Church is examining ways of simplifying its organisational
structure.
Canon John Stanley, a member of the Lambeth Group, said he found it
difficult to believe that Pounds 380m had been borrowed without reference to
the commissioners' board of governors.
The General Synod also attacked the government's policy of pit closures
yesterday. The Bishop of Sheffield, the Rt Rev David Lunn, said: 'It seems
to me quite amazing that ruthless treatment of the environment and
communities can take place without proper consultation. This is an act of
vandalism.'
</TEXT>
