<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Forest sell-offs plan attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRIVATISATION of the Forestry Commission's properties, which is being
studied by the government, would produce a meagre sum for the Treasury and
lead to greater recurrent expenditure on forestry and reduced income for the
state.
This is the view of three former top executives of the Forestry Commission
who issued a public statement yesterday to say that privatisation is
'against the interests of the taxpayer, the private forest owner, the timber
industry, the conservation interest and the public who enjoy access to the
forest'.
Mr Gwyn Francis and Mr George Holmes, both former directors-general of the
commission, and Mr Toby Seal, a former chief research officer, say that the
commission's 1.1m hectares of forest might only raise Pounds 500m in a
'forced sale'. This contrasts with its 1992 book value of Pounds 1.7bn.
They say that if the forests were sold the government would have to hand out
more money in grants to the new owners for planting and restocking, as well
as providing more management grants and other items whose additional costs
in 2000 would total Pounds 44m.
Taking into account the annual loss of Pounds 20m in timber sales, the total
additional cost to the exchequer would be Pounds 64m. By 2010 this would
have risen to Pounds 83m because of increased planting and restocking, and
lost timber sales.
Ministers reviewing the future of the commission and the incentives for tree
planting are due to report next year.
</TEXT>
