<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Electric sector in a new light: A retailing probe revealed
big losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF IT achieved nothing else, yesterday's report from Professor Stephen
Littlechild, the electricity regulator, highlighted the huge size of the
electricity companies' losses on their high-street retailing operations - a
total of Pounds 105m over the last three years.
But what effect will it have on the intensely competitive electrical and
electronic goods market?
Neither the electricity regulator nor the Office of Fair Trading - which
also looked into Dixons' allegations - found any evidence to support its
claim that the 12 regional electricity companies in England and Wales had
engaged in unfair cross-subsidisation of their retail businesses, or in
anti-competitive practices.
Dixons had charged that regional electricity companies helped their
electrical goods retailers in a variety of ways, for example, by bearing
part of their advertising and marketing costs, providing cheap
accommodation, providing capital at no charge, and joint billing services.
This help enabled them to increase market share by 2 percentage points to
about 13 per cent, Dixons said.
Prof Littlechild points out that the losses the companies are making in this
business are at the expense of the shareholder, not the electricity
consumer, who is protected by the official price tariff. 'Whether it is
commercially sensible to incur such losses is a matter for shareholders,' he
says.
Most of Prof Littlechild's recommendations for clearer and more consistent
accounting treatment of retail-ing operations have already been adopted by
several companies.
There is little more that he can do. These are non-core businesses which lie
outside his direct control.
But if yesterday's reports do not raise wider issues, they could have an
impact by turning the spotlight on the companies' difficulties in the high
street.
This might hasten the retreat many are already beating from the retailing
market. For example, Prof Littlechild's report looks beyond the
profit-and-loss account to comment that the companies' returns on capital
employed have been, on average, negative and in all cases low by the
standards proposed by Dixons.
Only one company, Norweb, could be described as on a strongly expansionary
course in retailing. London Electricity and Swalec in south Wales have
pulled out of the business, while others have decided to join forces. For
example, Eastern, Southern and Midlands have formed E&amp;S Retail.
A small number are still operating on their own, for example Seeboard, which
has opted for building superstores. Mr John Weight, the director responsible
for retailing, stressed yesterday, however, that expansion was 'measured and
controlled'.
</TEXT>
