<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Top brains 'still draining away'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'BRAIN DRAIN' of qualified scientists and engineers from the UK is
slowing down, but migration is concentrated on the highest quality staff 'to
the detriment of the UK', the Royal Society says today.
Between 1984 and last year, 13.5 per cent of recently qualified British PhDs
chose to leave the country - almost identical to the size of the migration
between 1975 and 1985. There were small falls in the numbers of more senior
staff leaving.
European Union countries have gained in popularity compared with the US,
suggesting closer integration of UK and Continental research.
Immigration to UK research groups increased from 2.9 per cent to 4.0 per
cent. The Royal Society, which produced the report jointly with the Royal
Academy of Engineering, urged caution because academics leaving tended to be
of the highest quality. Those leaving did so for professional reasons to
take up long-term posts, while those arriving in the UK tended to be taking
short-term posts.
Returning British emigrants 'overwhelmingly' did so for personal rather than
professional reasons.
Chemistry has suffered the greatest increase in migration, with 16.2 per
cent of recently qualified chemists leaving the UK between 1984 and last
year, compared with 12 per cent between 1975 and 1985.
The migration of scientists and engineers 1984-92, SEPSU Policy Study No. 8.
Publication Sales Dept, 6 Carlton House Terrace, London SW1Y 5AG. Pounds 25
(Pounds 27 overseas).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
