<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Exchange head considers overhaul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY OF the London Stock Exchange's functions may be modified or abandoned
after Mr Michael Lawrence, the newly-named chief executive of the stock
exchange, takes up his duties next February.
'I don't see that there is anything that is fixed in stone. There are no
no-go areas,' Mr Lawrence, said yesterday.
Mr Lawrence, finance director at Prudential, the UK's largest life insurance
company, and a former partner at accountancy firm Price Waterhouse, who is
to review the exchange's activities once in place, said he had been
attracted to his new job because of the widespread view that the role of the
exchange needed to change.
He refused to offer a view about some of the most difficult issues facing
the exchange, such as whether it should own and operate its own settlement
system, such as the proposed Pounds 57m successor to its SEAQ price display
mechanism. 'I want to start with a white sheet,' he said.
The only criterion, he said, was that the exchange should remain the central
market in the UK for equity trading.
Mr Lawrence spelled out what he sees as the role for the new chairman who
will succeed Sir Andrew Hugh Smith next November. The new chairman - whose
identity is known to Mr Lawrence but not yet announced - will be a part-time
employee who will act largely as ambassador for the exchange in the City and
in foreign markets.
'I see a major role in recasting the vision for the exchange and carrying
that vision to the City at large,' he said. He and other exchange officials
would influence the development of that vision although his own duties would
focus on operational matters.
As finance director for a large company and chairman of the 100 Group of
Finance Directors Mr Lawrence is thought to be much closer to the interests
of the companies whose shares are traded on the exchange than his
predecessor, Mr Peter Rawlins. Also, he is thought likely to be more
sensitive to the interests of investors than the present senior management
of the exchange.
Mr Lawrence does not consider himself a City outsider but concedes that he
has not worked in a dealing room.
His background is already prompting some expressions of concern from
market-makers. On said: 'Listed companies and institutional investors are
basically our clients. If he starts getting in the way it's going to go
wrong.'
Editorial comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
