<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Names under pressure to accept settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF London may attempt to 'bounce' loss-making Names into accepting
an out-of-court settlement to legal disputes at the insurance market, the
chairman of the biggest action group of loss makers warned yesterday.
Mr Michael Deeny told the annual meeting of the Gooda Walker Action
Groupthat Names would soon 'receive a barrage of mail warning you that this
is the last offer.'
The warning comes amid indications that some Lloyd's agents - who handle the
affairs of the Names that support the market - may also oppose Lloyd's plans
to ask them to make voluntary contributions to help fund a settlement.
The agents, who are targetted in more than two dozen legal actions, will
learn today how their contributions are to be calculated.
More than 100 agencies could be asked to donate, but the losses of Lloyd's
in recent years have stretched available resources of some smaller
companies.
The managing director of another agency said: 'Many agents will not be in a
position to find that sort of money.'
At the Gooda meeting Mr Deeny said the 3,000 Gooda Names should press ahead
with their legal action rather than accept an inadequate deal. Offers of
compensation in the region of 30p in the pound, a figure widely rumoured at
the Lloyd's market, were way below levels that 'the committee of this action
group could recommend to its membership.'
Mr Deeny said: 'Multilateral negotiations of a most complex and demanding
nature' were taking place between the leaders of loss making Names, Lloyd's,
agents and their insurers but no 'concrete or detailed offer' was on the
table.
Lloyd's wants to finance a deal through contributions from errors and
omissions insurers, which cover Lloyd's agents against awards for
negligence, and the Lloyd's central fund. It is understood that E&amp;O insurers
might provide Pounds 300m towards a settlement. Lloyd's said two months ago
that it would also seek contributions from agents, brokers and accountants.
It is understood that the formula on which agents' contributions will be
based takes into account three factors: the deductibles (the amount of an
insurance claim paid by the buyer) on the agents' errors and omissions
insurance policies; the amounts of exposure not insured by these policies;
and the exposure of each agent to potential claims.
Agency boards will meet next week to examine the implications of the scheme.
Annual deductibles are typically between Pounds 300,000 and Pounds 500,000
for bigger agents.
One agent estimated that between Pounds 25m and Pounds 75m could be raised
through such contributions but that the cost might push many smaller agents
into insolvency.
</TEXT>
