<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Polly Peck administrators quizzed over bribes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL JORDAN, ad-ministrator to Polly Peck International, the collapsed
fruit to electronics group, yesterday appeared before the Istanbul public
prosecutor's office to answer questions relating to allegations made by Mr
Asil Nadir that administrators considered bribing customs officials.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the UK auditors, last night claimed that the move was 'a
minor attempt to put a spanner in the works in an effort to forcibly
postpone Mr Jordan's visit to Cyprus'.
Mr Jordan and Mr David Kidd of Coopers were visited by police in their hotel
room late on Wednesday night. Police took their passports and they were
requested to appear the following morning, when they were questioned for
three hours. Their passports were later returned. British consular officials
were last night trying to establish on what grounds the request had been
made.
The prosecutor's move follows a complaint lodged by Mr Nadir's lawyer
connected with the continuing dispute over ownership of AN Graphics, an
Istanbul printing concern claimed by the administrators. Sources confirm
that the company was transferred to Mr Nadir for 'nil consideration', just
three days before the courts appointed the administrators in October 1990.
The bribery allegations relate to an internal memo, a copy of which Mr Nadir
released yesterday.
The administrators concede that the memo deployed what one official called
'loose wording', including reference to the need for bribes to Turkish
customs to release a disputed piece of printing equipment belonging to AN
Graphics.
On Wednesday Mr Ali Riza Gorgun, Mr Nadir's lawyer in North Cyprus, said the
Turkish prosecutor had issued a warrant for the arrest of all three
administrators - Mr Jordan, Mr Richard Stone and Mr Christopher Morris.
Mr Jordan was due back in London last night and Mr Gorgun was uncontactable.
The incident forced Mr Jordan to cancel a trip to northern Cyprus to attend
court hearings in Nicosia today on the injunctions over the various PPI
companies on the island.
It marks the latest tactic by Mr Nadir to block the administrators access to
the Polly Peck companies. Mr Nadir jumped bail in May fleeing the UK where
he faces charges of theft and false accounting relating to Polly Peck.
