<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Minister defends truancy tables
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERFORMANCE tables of school truancy rates are essential to the government's
'back to basics' campaign, Baroness Blatch, the education minister, said
yesterday.
She said high truancy rates had contributed to the rising crime rate. 'Not
every truant is a potential criminal. Some may be at home watching
television,' she said.
'But where teenagers or even very young children are wandering the streets -
as many do - they are all too vulnerable to criminal or anti-social
influences.'
She told a conference on truancy, organised by the University of North
London, that the Department for Education, which will next week publish the
first truancy tables, had received responses from 95 per cent of schools in
England and Wales in spite of an attempt to boycott them by the National
Association of Head Teachers.
The government plans to extend the tables to include authorised as well as
unauthorised absences, following complaints that some schools are less
stringent than others. She said parentally-condoned truancy was a particular
problem for some schools.
Baroness Blatch added that information technology and monitoring systems
might have a role to play for schools combating the problem.
Dr Dennis O'Keeffe, director of the university's truancy unit, told the
conference he was sceptical about a direct link between truancy and crime.
He said, however, that a survey by the university had suggested that 30.5
per cent of pupils in their last two years of compulsory schooling played
truant at least once.
He found that the largest cause was dissatisfaction with lessons, cited by
two-thirds of truants.
Fear of disapproval by parents and teachers was the most powerful control on
truants, suggesting that 'school ethos is the critical variable' in fighting
truancy.
</TEXT>
