FT  12 NOV 93 / Troubled Ford picks new sales director
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD of Britain, which has suffered three years of heavy losses and a steady
erosion of its share of the UK new car market, yesterday appointed Mr Paddy
Byrne as sales director.
The reshuffling of its top management follows the appointment of Mr Ernie
Thompson, its long-serving sales director, as chief executive of the Society
of Motor Manufacturers and Traders.
Mr Byrne, who has been Ford of Europe's director of East European sales and
export operations for the past two years, was previously chief executive of
the troubled Waterford Wedgwood glassware and china group.
The appointment of Mr Thompson as SMMT chief executive marks a sharp change
of direction by the association. He succeeds Sir Hal Miller, former
Conservative MP and joint chairman of the House of Commons all-party motor
industry group.
Mr Thompson's Ford background could prove divisive. Ford has voiced loud
criticism of the growing Japanese presence in the industry, which it says is
posing a direct threat to the existing motor industry technology base.
Nissan, the Japanese carmaker, is now a full member of the SMMT, however,
and other Japanese carmakers, Toyota and Honda, are expected to play a
growing role.
