<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Former electronics chief cleared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROY ASHMAN, the former chairman of Harland Simons, the electronics
company, was acquitted yesterday at Aylesbury Crown Court of making
misleading statements to two investors shortly before a reduced profits
forecast caused the company's share price to fall.
The jury's verdict after the five-day trial represents a disappointment for
the Department of Trade and Industry which brought the prosecution under
Section 47 of the Financial Services Act, which outlaws the making of
misleading statements.
The case was the fourth to be brought under Section 47 since the passing of
the legislation. Section 47 has been under close scrutiny by lawyers and
regulators since its introduction. Of the four prosecutions to date two have
succeeded and two have failed.
Mr Ashman had been accused of misleading two fund managers from Govett
Strategic Investments by telling them, at a meeting last February, that he
was comfortable with the company's initial forecast of profits of about
Pounds 13m to Pounds 14m.
The two fund managers, Mr Nigel Savage and Mr Marc Gordon, then bought
155,000 shares worth almost Pounds 1m in the group. Just hours later the
profits forecast was reduced to Pounds 4m and the share price fell from 585p
to 270p.
The company eventually reported a pre-tax loss of more than Pounds 6m.
Mr Ashman denied knowing at the time of the meeting that the profit forecast
was about to be reduced.
He also told the court that Mr Savage had been 'getting around to questions
he should not have been asking' about anticipated year-end returns.
Mr Ashman refused to comment after the verdict. His solicitor, Mr Graham
Huntley said: 'We are very happy with the result and it is unfortunate that
this prosecution was brought in the first place.'
</TEXT>
