<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Building societies want broader lending rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES are urging their regulator to soften the force of planned
guidance on lending policy, saying that it is too detailed and prescriptive
in its present form.
They have warned that the draft prudential note put forward by the Building
Societies Commission could inhibit their ability to compete in mortgage
lending unless it is changed. The 40-page draft sets out guidance covering
the whole range of a society's lending, including issues such as assessing
risks, limiting exposure to fixed rate and capped lending, and dealing with
arrears.
Prudential notes have a particular status in the way that building societies
are regulated. Any society which does not comply with such a note normally
has to explain itself to the commission and might also find its credit
rating affected.
Several of the larger societies have already expressed their concerns to the
commission, and these are reflected in a response from the Building
Societies Association, the industry's trade body. The unease is felt
particularly strongly as lending is one of societies' core activities.
Issues of contention include the ways of assessing a borrower's ability to
repay a mortgage and a society's exposure to fixed-rate mortgages.
Societies have recently been losing their share of the mortgage lending
market to banks, whose fixed-rate mortgages have proved particularly
popular.
In the face of the industry pressure the commission is likely to back down
and agree to issue the guidance in a different form, which carries less
weight.
The association suggested that only broad guidance should be contained in a
prudential note, and that more detailed advice about what is 'best practice'
could be issued separately, perhaps by the association rather than by the
commission.
Societies are also concerned that parts of the guidance are not suited to
the whole of the industry from Halifax, the UK's largest society, to the
smallest operators in the sector.
Some of the largest societies believe that in certain lending issues the
commission should seek to reach agreements with individual societies instead
of trying to set blanket limits for the industry as a whole.
Mr Andrew Longhurst, chief executive of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, the UK's
sixth largest society, said the draft guidance was part of a trend which
could see the commission moving increasingly into societies' operational
matters.
He said: 'A common view in the industry is that the commission is getting
into realms that could be commercial rather than prudential.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
