<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Levitt Group was 'riddled with fraud': Deception of Fimbra
alleged at first day of trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEVITT GROUP, the failed financial services company, was 'riddled with
fraud, forgery, deception and downright dishonesty' in the 18 months before
its collapse in December 1990, it was alleged at the Old Bailey yesterday.
Mr David Cocks QC, prosecuting for the Serious Fraud Office, said Mr Roger
Levitt, the company's chairman, illegally injected funds, forged accounts
and misled Fimbra, the Levitt Group's regulator, to conceal its massive
losses and continue trading.
Mr Cocks was opening the prosecution's case against Mr Levitt and three
other former executives of the company, Mr Mark Reed, Mr Alan McNamara and
Mr Robert Price.
All four deny a charge of fraudulent trading that alleges the production of
false accounts, the fraudulent injection of almost Pounds 21m into the
company and the misleading of Fimbra about the state of Levitt Group
finances.
Mr Cocks told the jury the Levitt Group had grown from humble beginnings in
the middle 1970s, when it sold only pensions, to a concern recording profits
of Pounds 8m in 1988.
By then it was providing a range of investment, tax and financial services
to wealthy clients. Mr Roger Levitt, the driving force behind the company,
was a 'past master as a salesman', he said.
By early 1989, however, the company was in desperate financial trouble and
heading for collapse. Between January 1989 and June 1990 the group made
losses of Pounds 13m.
'In 1989 the decline and fall of the empire was well on the way. Bankers and
others dealing with the Levitt Group thought it was a thriving concern. It
fact it was an empty shell making huge losses,' Mr Cocks said. He added that
the company could be kept afloat only by fraud and dishonesty on a massive
scale.
'Money had to be pumped into that leaky vessel to keep it afloat at all,' Mr
Cocks said.
He alleged that between April 1989 and December 1990 Mr Levitt illegally
injected almost Pounds 21m into his ailing company. The money came from
personal loans, share sales and other sources, including Pounds 400,000
invested by Mr Frederick Forsyth, the author, who thought the money would be
placed in bonds.
Mr Cocks said the company's books then had to be 'cooked' to present this
money as genuine income. Fee notes and invoices were forged to show that the
Pounds 21m had come from Mr Levitt's provision of 'personal services' to
clients.
The book-cooking exercise proved so rigorous and thorough that the group's
Pounds 13m loss was turned into a stated profit of almost the same amount.
Assets were also manipulated so that the company accounts recorded a healthy
surplus rather than a 'thumping loss', Mr Cocks said.
Without these stated figures, giving the impression of a successful company,
nobody would have dealt with the Levitt Group and it would have collapsed,
he said.
The fraud also depended on the misleading of Fimbra to ensure that the
regulator maintained its authorisation of the group, he added. Although Stoy
Hayward, the company's auditors, had been 'taken in' by the false accounts,
Fimbra was not satisfied. Helped by the accounting firm, it started an
investigation.
This led to the group's suspension from Fimbra membership and liquidation in
December 1990 with debts of Pounds 34m.
Mr Levitt was the 'architect' of the fraud, with Mr Mark Reed, his
'right-hand man' since 1976, the other main protagonist, Mr Cocks said.
The prosecution said that although Mr Price left the company in mid-1990, he
had been involved in the fraud as finance director and Mr McNamara, a former
commercial director, was also involved. Mr Cocks told the jury that Mr
McNamara had told police: 'When Levitt said jump, I jumped.'
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Levitt Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9211 Courts.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
