<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / UN tightens Lockerbie sanctions on Libya
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   ByMICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS AT THE UN and MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council last night voted to tighten sanctions against Libya
in a new effort to bring the two men accused of the Lockerbie airliner
bombing to trial in Scotland or the US.
The measures include freezing Libyan financial assets abroad, strengthening
an existing ban on international air links by closing all foreign offices of
the Libyan airline, and halting exports to Libya of oil refining and
pipeline equipment.
In addition, funds derived from Libya's oil and natural gas sales and from
agricultural products must be paid into separate and exclusive bank
accounts.
Eleven member nations of the Security Council voted for the resolution.
There were no votes against it but China, Pakistan, Morocco and Djibouti
abstained.
Libya so far has refused to hand over the two men accused of blowing up the
Pan American airliner which disintegrated over Lockerbie in Scotland in 1988
with the loss of 270 lives.
The latest measures will not go into effect until December 1, giving Mr
Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary general, extra time to try to
negotiate a solution.
The new sanctions are likely to have a psychological rather than an
immediate economic impact on Libya, particularly as they leave untouched its
hydrocarbon export revenues, which amounted to Dollars 9.5bn last year -
some 95 per cent of hard currency earnings.
Closure of the state airline offices merely tightens an existing ban on air
travel, an inconvenience Libyans have got used to since April 1992. Most of
Libya's imports arrive by sea or road.
The ban on parts and spares for the country's oil transport and export
facilities is designed to erode its export capacity.
There were hints last month that Libya might surrender the accused men for
trial in Scotland but this came to nothing, ostensibly because their lawyers
objected.
An offer to hold the proceedings in Switzerland, which Mr Ali Ahmed
Elhouderi, the Libyan delegate, repeated at the UN yesterday, has been
rejected by Britain. The Libyan delegate insisted that only the venue was in
dispute, not the question of holding a trial.
The resolution was carefully drafted to cause as little interference as
possible with western Europe's economic relations with Libya or with
exploration contracts signed recently by Total of France, Eni-Agip of Italy
and Petrofina of Belgium.
In a bid to protect its own economic interests, including Libya's Dollars
4bn debt-for-arms purchases, Russia at first threatened to block the
resolution. President Boris Yeltsin relented in response to personal appeals
by President Bill Clinton and Mr John Major, the British prime minister.
Russia voted for the resolution, which at its insistence included an
affirmation of 'Libya's duty scrupulously to adhere to all of its
obligations concerning servicing and repayment of its foreign debt'.
Delaying imposition of the new measures until next month was also a Russian
proposal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>LYZ  Libya, Africa.
</CN>
