<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Arafat halts trip to face critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR YASSIR Arafat, chairman of the PLO, cut short a visit to Portugal
yesterday and flew to Tunis for emergency meetings, amid mounting criticism
of his management of political and economic talks with Israel and
international donors.
Mr Nabil Amr, an adviser to Mr Arafat, said a group of PLO officials had
drafted a document criticising the chairman's political and negotiating
performance.
Israel's Finance Ministry said it had still not got a message from Mr Arafat
confirming the start of critical economic talks due to open in Paris on
Monday. The talks will set the agenda for future economic relations and
decide whether there will be a customs union.
Palestinians and international donors have voiced strong criticism of lack
of leadership on economic policy as the date for Palestinian self-government
in the occupied territories draws near. A World Bank official said this week
the PLO had to move swiftly to appoint professional personnel for the
recently announced Economic Council for Development and Construction.
