<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 93 / Investment shake-up for French TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A reshuffle of domestic shareholdings in French television is expected to
result from this week's bill allowing single investors to increase their
stakes from 25 to 49 per cent in a TV station, David Buchan reports from
Paris.
When TF1, France's leading TV station, was privatised, and newer private
channels such as M6 and Canal Plus were set up, the 25 per cent limit was
considered necessary to prevent a concentration of media power. But many
large investors have complained that the limit gives them financial
liability, without management control.
The bill is unlikely to change the fact that French TV is considered off
limits to foreigners.
</TEXT>
