<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow climbs despite rising
bond yields
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AIDED BY heavy program trading, US share prices posted solid gains yesterday
as investors shrugged off rising bond yields and disappointing inflation and
employment news, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 23.48 ahead at 3,663.55 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 3.39 at 463.72, while the Nasdaq composite
advanced 6.66 to 776.50. NYSE volume was 283.4m shares.
Equity prices struggled from the opening as rising bond yields unsettled
market sentiment. The bond market was reacting to strengthening commodities
prices and the latest news on inflation - a 0.4 per cent rise in the October
consumer price index. Although the increase was broadly in line with
analysts' forecasts, after Tuesday's much better than expected producer
prices data, the stock and bond markets had been hoping that the consumer
prices figures would be equally encouraging.
The increase in bond yields immediately fed through into lower equities, and
investors were also troubled by a jump in weekly unemployment insurance
claims. The early losses, however, were not substantial, and smaller-company
stocks actually started the day with solid gains. By midday the markets had
recovered their poise, and by the afternoon a series of buy programs had
pushed stocks further into positive territory.
Semiconductor issues were bought on reports of strong demand for the
companies' products. Only last week the sector was hit by selling on concern
about sales. Texas Instruments forged ahead Dollars 4 to Dollars 63 1/8 ,
Motorola Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 102 7/8 , National Semiconductor Dollars 1
3/4 to Dollars 17 7/8 and Storage Technology Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 29 1/2
.
Paramount Communications fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 80 5/8 in busy
trading after administrators handling the disposal of the business empire of
Mr Robert Maxwell announced that his Macmillan publishing group would be
sold to Paramount for just over Dollars 1bn.
Telefonos de Mexico rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 52 3/8 as investors
suggested that the chances of the Nafta pact passing congress in a crucial
vote next week had been boosted by Tuesday night's televised debate between
US Vice-president Al Gore and Nafta opponent Mr Ross Perot.
Walt Disney lost Dollars 1 to Dollars 40 1/4 in early trading before
recovering to end unchanged at Dollars 41 1/4 in volume of 3.4m shares after
announcing that it would help fund its Euro Disney subsidiary while
exploring a possible financial restructuring of the troubled theme park.
Canada
TORONTO hit a record peak in the second-busiest day of trading ever on the
exchange. The TSE 300 index ended 18.1 higher at 4,269.5, with advances
outpacing declines by 443 to 340 after volume of 99.3m shares valued at
CDollars 698m.
</TEXT>
