<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / International Company News: BellSouth provides Dollars 1.2bn
for shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BELLSOUTH, the largest Baby Bell regional telephone company, announced
yesterday that it is to take a Dollars 1.2bn restructuring charge in the
fourth quarter for modernising its network and cutting its workforce by
10,200 over the next three years.
The move comes as the company is weighing whether to join the takeover
battle for entertainment group Paramount Communications by making an
investment in QVC Network, the home shopping channel making a Dollars 9.7bn
hostile bid for the company. Paramount has agreed to a Dollars 10bn takeover
proposal from cable group Viacom.
BellSouth, which provides the local telephone service in the south-eastern
US, is the latest of several regional telecommunications groups taking large
charges to slim down and modernise their operations to cope with growing
competition in the previously monopolistic market.
The company said that the charge, which would reduce net income by Dollars
760m, or Dollars 1.53 a share, was to cover re-engineering of its local
exchange network which would be completed by the end of 1996.
It was 'dramatically changing the way it works with customers, redesigning
its fundamental processes and streamlining systems for handling customer
service'.
Some Dollars 550m of the charge relates to the introduction of new systems,
while Dollars 310m covers consolidating and eliminating certain operations
and Dollars 380m is for job losses.
</TEXT>
