<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / International Company News: Walt Disney hit by Dollars 350m
charge for French park
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WALT Disney, the US entertainment group, yesterday reported a fourth-quarter
net loss of Dollars 77.8m after taking a Dollars 350m charge associated with
Euro Disney, the troubled French theme park in which it holds a 49 per cent
stake.
The company reported a 10 per cent drop in operating income, from Dollars
395.8m to Dollars 356.7m, on revenues which rose 5 per cent to Dollars
2.2bn, while the net loss worked through at 15 cents a share. In the fourth
quarter of last year Disney made Dollars 224m, or 42 cents a share.
Wall Street analysts were generally sanguine about the lower-than-expected
operating results, pointing to special factors, but some trimmed their 1994
earnings forecasts because of the large losses at Euro Disney. Salomon
Brothers, for example, cut its projection from Dollars 2.05 a share to
Dollars 1.85.
Walt Disney's investment in Euro Disney produced a loss of Dollars 414.5m
for the quarter - including the Dollars 350m charge - and a loss of Dollars
514m for the full year.
Walt Disney said the need for a financial restructuring at Euro Disney had
created uncertainty about the American company's ability to collect its
current receivables from Euro Disney and about its provision of temporary
funding to the associate. Its Dollars 350m charge would fully reserve it
against both, with roughly 50 per cent of the sum accounted for by the
funding.
Walt Disney's theme parks and resorts saw operating income fall 11 per cent
in the quarter to Dollars 190.4m on revenues down 6 per cent at Dollars
933.7m.
Filmed entertainment saw operating income down 22 per cent at Dollars 94.9m
on revenues up 12 per cent to Dollars 879.8m. The company attributed the
drop to an unusually strong 1992 fourth quarter.
For the full year, Disney reported net income of Dollars 299m, or 55 cents a
share, down from Dollars 816m, or Dollars 1.52 a share, after accounting
changes and Euro Disney charges. Its operating income rose 20 per cent to
Dollars 1.72bn on revenues 14 per cent higher at Dollars 8.5bn.
</TEXT>
