<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / International Company News: SAS plunges to SKr1.75bn deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SCANDINAVIAN Airlines System (SAS) has plunged into a SKr1.75bn (Dollars
216m) loss after financial items for the first nine months, sharply
reversing the SKr592m profit it made in the same 1992 period.
The deterioration underlines the urgency of the group's efforts to merge
with three other European airlines - KLM Royal Dutch, Swissair and Austrian
Airlines - in the Alcazar project.
It has led the airline to promise 'an intensive result improvement
programme' to help it get back into profit. The measures being considered
include job losses, route closures, and the sale and leaseback of aircraft.
SAS blamed its deficit on the weakening of the Swedish krona, which produced
unrealised exchange losses of SKr1.15bn.
A 2 per cent drop in passenger yields and losses on hotel and leisure
operations aggravated its position.
Operating revenues climbed 15 per cent to SKr29.2bn, but this was
outstripped by a 21 per cent rise in expenses to SKr27.4bn.
The airline admits it has fallen behind schedule on a targeted 8 per cent
cut in costs this year, and is promising to beef up the efficiency drive in
1994.
Pre-tax losses were held to SKr1.13bn after a SKr500m gain from the sale of
part of SAS Service Partner, the airline's catering unit.
The airline benefited from a 2 per cent increase in passengers to 14.1m,
while traffic in revenue passenger kilometres was up 7 per cent from last
year.
The most difficult market has been Sweden, where deregulation has brought a
14 per cent decline in traffic.
Compensating for this was favourable growth on European, Intercontinental
and domestic Norwegian routes.
SAS expects its full-year figures to show a slight improvement over the
nine-month results, helped by a stronger Swedish krona.
Mr Jan Carlzon, who stepped down as chief executive of SAS in September to
add impetus to the Alcazar talks, yesterday warned that the merger project
would collapse if the European carriers could not agree on the choice of a
US partner before the end of this month.
His remarks were quoted in the Swedish daily Svenska Dagbladet, which said
SAS was planning to cut 3,000 out of 39,000 jobs.
</TEXT>
