<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Unigate helped to 20% rise by acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A ONE-FIFTH rise in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 50.3m at Unigate, the
food and distribution group, was 'a good performance in difficult trading
conditions,' chairman Sir Brian Kellett said.
However, the rise owed much to acquisitions and one-off items. The group
warned that profits growth would slow in the second half.
Mr Ross Buckland, chief executive, said promotions by retailers were causing
sharp fluctuations in fresh food volume, which made production inefficient
and squeezed margins.
He said Unigate would work aggressively with retailers not against them. But
he questioned whether retailers would benefit from price cutting. 'I would
suggest not,' he said.
Price cuts had particularly hit low-fat spreads and yoghurts. However, good
volume growth had been achieved in desserts.
Operating profits from dairies rose by half to Pounds 18.6m as acquisitions,
such as Clifford Foods, were integrated. Three dairies had been closed and
the group now produced a third more milk.
Mr Buckland said the dairy business had a good future, although doorstep
deliveries of milk - where margins are higher - were declining at an annual
rate of 10 to 12 per cent. Margins on supermarket milk were unsatisfactory,
he said, although volumes had risen.
Unigate, which has 16 per cent of the liquid milk market in England and
Wales, would be 'pleased to buy milk in whichever way dairy farmers wish to
sell it,' once the Milk Marketing Board was abolished next year. He was
confident the group could buy the amount of milk it needed at the right
price under the auction system proposed by Milk Marque, the successor body.
During the half there was a cash outflow of Pounds 70.1m, of which Pounds
20.1m represented excess of acquisitions over disposals. This increased net
debt to Pounds 172.1m from Pounds 98.2m at the previous year-end, giving
gearing of 52.8 per cent.
The interest charge rose from Pounds 4.7m to Pounds 7.1m, but interest cover
was 'healthy' at seven times, Mr John Worby, finance director, said.
The rise in debt was partly caused by the cancellation of the sale of
Unigate's US restaurant business. Mr Buckland said the aim was to float this
in the next 12 to 18 months, but Unigate could make more acquisitions before
then. He indicated these could be in continental Europe.
Observer, Page 19; London SE, Page 44; Lex, Page 20; Details, Page 23
