<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Lone-parent claimants up sharply, official data show
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE MPs urged the government yesterday to press ahead with its
examination of ways to cut state benefit to single-parent families after new
data showed a sharp rise in the number of lone parents claiming social
security in recent years.
Government figures showed that the number of lone parents claiming income
support, one of the main benefits disbursed by the Department of Social
Security, had risen by more than 38 per cent in the past five years.
Nearly half those claimants were single women, and 45 per cent of all
claimants had received the benefit for more than two years.
The release of the figures coincided with a row in Westminster over whether
ministers were planning to cut state benefit to lone parents in an attempt
to reduce the social security budget.
On Tuesday, a leaked cabinet document had claimed that the growth in the
number of lone parents was 'a burden on public expenditure'. It also
disclosed that ministers were considering cutting state benefits.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, played down the prospect that
the government would cut benefits to that group.
But yesterday, Mr Alan Duncan, a backbench Tory MP and member of the Commons
select committee on social security, said the data were another indication
that a 'culture' of lone mothers was growing.
'We must pursue our survey of how much this is costing and we are entitled
to ask whether any cuts in the costs can be made,' he said.
Yesterday's figures showed nearly 1m lone parents claiming benefit in summer
1992, compared with 694,000 in May 1988.
The number of lone parents claiming income support as a proportion of all
claimants had also risen over that period, from 16 per cent to 18.8 per
cent.
Lone parents also turned out to be the largest single category of claimants
for housing benefit last year, ahead of the disabled and the unemployed.
These figures go some way towards explaining the rising cost to the state of
supporting lone parents - at Pounds 6.6bn DSS in the 1992-93 financial year,
about 8 per cent of the total social security budget.
Mr Donald Dewar, Labour's social security secretary, said the figures
underlined that the government had to increase childcare provision and
educational opportunities. 'We have learnt this week that policy is
conducted from prejudice and not from facts,' he said.
</TEXT>
