FT  11 NOV 93 / The Lex Column: News Corporation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rupert Murdoch has hardly put a foot wrong recently, as his latest burst
of deal-making and the 10-fold increase in News Corporation's shares since
1991 testify. But he trod in something nasty yesterday as News reported a 5
per cent fall in first-quarter operating profits and the controversy
resurfaced over its plans for a new class of super voting shares with a
discussion paper from the Australian stock exchange.
News's book publishing profits were weaker and problems grew at its
free-standing insert division. But the real hit came from its price-cutting
campaign in the UK, where newspaper profits slid 15 per cent. Thanks to his
non-executive directorship at Philip Morris, Mr Murdoch has had a ring-side
seat watching similar pricing punch-ups in the US. But Marlboro's assault
has led to a fearful bruising and US cigarette prices now appear to be
edging up again. The suspicion grows that any imposition of VAT on
newspapers would cloak restorative price rises on its UK titles.
The Australian stock exchange is treading gingerly over News's share
proposals. It may worry that if it blocks the scheme, its second most
heavily traded stock will switch its listing to the US. But that is no
reason to concede a point of principle. Besides, News can hardly count on an
ecstatic reception in New York. Calpers has been among the most vociferous
critics of the share proposal. Moreover, there was heavy selling of News's
ADRs after disappointment grew with its first-quarter results.
