<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Arts: Brooding Russian - Concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On Tuesday we should have heard Nikolai Demidenko playing Tchaikovsky and
Rakhmaninov piano trios in the Wigmore Hall, with his violin-compatriot
Grigori Zhislin and the French-Canadian cellist Sophie Rolland. But when we
got there, the concert had shrunk to a solo recital by Demidenko. I might
just have gone home; this formidable pianist compels admiration, but rarely
any sympathetic warmth. His last-minute programme included a lot of Nikolai
Medtner, however - two of whose concerti he recorded with electrifying
commitment last year; so I stayed.
Medtner is a peculiarly interesting composer: a contemporary of Skryabin and
Rakhmaninov, and hugely fluent - but unlike them a Westernising
'conservative', because his favoured models were Schumann and Brahms. He
fled Russia soon after the Revolution, and lived his last 30-odd years in
Golders Green.
Demidenko cuts rather a daunting figure: lofty, chilly, saturnine. His
Medtner here was the Sonata Reminiscenza and the Sonata Tragica, each of
them prefaced by a slighter piece from which it grew: a 'Canzona Serenata'
and a 'Canzona Matinata', respectively wistful and morning-dewy.
Viktoria Postnikova used to make a speciality of the Sonata Reminiscenza,
which flowed under her hands continuously and hauntingly, amid subtle
shadings. With Demidenko each new thematic idea arrived with a grinding
clash, as if Medtner's structures were held together by main force alone.
Moments of pungent character erupted as if from nowhere, lightning-flashes
in no cogent order. The laser-illuminations were brilliant, their sequence
fractured and unpersuasive.
Demidenko had begun his recital with Tchaikovsky's Dumka, virtually an
'occasional' piece - tuneful but little more than routine concert-stuff,
which he searched through with slow, excruciating tenderness, rather
marvellous to hear. The second half of his programme, all Rakhmaninov (three
Etudes-Tableaux, seven Preludes), was only fitfully concentrated. There was
a regular scatter of finger-slips, especially in rapid bass-shots - most
unlike Demidenko's usual omni-competent form.
The E-flat minor Etude-Tableau began with a nervily original kind of
brooding and ended in drawn-out gloom, but the middle was all-out,
triple-forte bashing. The programme-notes reported the expatriate Demidenko
as declaring that 'being Russian is a duty'] That may be so; but the duty
need not be so icy, nor so grimly stern.
</TEXT>
<XX>
