<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RTZ states that its mining companies in Papua New Guinea have consulted the
local people and complied with the environmental demands of the government.
Yet according to 'Hell In The Pacific' (C4, 9.00) in the Critical Eye
series, there has been much bitterness since the RTZ subsidiary CRA began
mining copper at Bougainville in 1966 and gold at Mount Kare in 1990.
Michael Ignatieff begins a six-part series on nationalism, Blood And
Belonging (BBC2, 9.30), in the former Yugoslavia where he lived as a child.
Since he was born in Canada, his father in Russia, and he now lives in
Britain, he seems particularly well equipped to present programmes which
visit all those countries.
Richard Briers stars as 'God' (Godfrey) in the four-part comedy If You See
God, Tell Him (BBC1, 9.30). When struck by a load of builder's rubble
Godfrey is transformed into 'a parody of the ad-man's dream': a disabled
pensioner who believes in advertisements as fundamentalists believe in The
Bible. ITV begins six short dramas set in London's tube train system: Going
Undergound (11.15).
</TEXT>
