<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Political Notebook: The National Insurance fiction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEBATE about the welfare state will not go away. What started as a
Treasury exercise to regain a grip on public spending after the excesses of
the late 1980s and the recession of the early 1990s has become entwined
inextricably in the internal politics of Mr John Major's government.
No matter that the ambitious social engineering envisaged by one or two in
the cabinet is regarded by most of their colleagues as wistful rhetoric -
witness the latest furore over single mothers. Nor that more sober analyses
about the future costs of welfare provision, such as this week's report from
the Rowntree Foundation, invariably undercut the gloomy demographic
projections of Treasury pessimists. Unemployment, not an ageing population,
is the principal enemy of prudent control of welfare spending.
But the government has more narrow perspectives. There is the pressing need
to justify the harsh measures to contain public spending over the next few
years. Whatever the prospects in 2020, the present Pounds 80bn social
security budget is pre-empting what limited scope there is for higher
spending elsewhere.
Then there is Mr Major's search for a patch of political ground on which the
still-disgruntled right of his party can stand. For those who have not
forgiven him for deriding the 'golden age that never was' a debate on the
role of the state has become the acid test of his commitment to
reconciliation.
So Mr Michael Portillo, the guardian both of the Treasury's purse strings
and of the Thatcherite inheritance, is set free each week to ponder publicly
about rolling back the frontiers of the state.
During his latest appearance he worried aloud about the 'massive' amount of
Britain's income being taken in taxation and spent by the government. By
pre-empting 45 per cent of national income the state was threatening to
strangle the wealth creation process and undermine fatally Britain's
competitiveness.
There were dangerous social consequences. An ingrained assumption that the
state would provide was undermining the essential Conservative concepts of
individual responsibility and self-reliance.
There was no mention, of course, that this dire state of affairs followed 14
years of Tory government. Mr Portillo is as adept as any at drawing lines
under the awkwardness of the past.
Mr Portillo takes as an example the basic pension. Instead of paying into
the National Insurance Fund and expecting a state pension on retirement, he
suggests, people should use the money instead to buy their own insurance for
old age.
At first sight it seems an entirely reasonable proposition. No-one would be
worse off as most people would simply collect their pension from an
insurance company. A safety net system, of course, would remain in place for
the disadvantaged. But then comes the political roadblock that even the bold
Mr Portillo is not prepared to confront. His argument is built on the flimsy
fiction that the National Insurance Fund is what it pretends to be - a fund.
It is no such thing. The Pounds 38bn a year paid in National Insurance
contributions by the present generation of employers and employees is not
salted away to meet future liabilities. It is used to pay the benefits owed
to a past generation.
But to admit the fiction would be politically explosive. The price would be
public acknowledgement that contributions are indistinguishable from income
tax and that the basic rate of income tax is 34 per cent not 25 per cent -
and that from next April it will rise to 35 per cent.
Mr Portillo sidesteps the resultant flaw in his argument. The present
generation of contributors could not replace their present National
Insurance payments with private provision without impoverishing today's
elderly. The chief secretary is instead asking the under-40s to continue
paying the fund's past liabilities while foregoing any future benefits.
Perhaps Mr Portillo believes that is unavoidable. The Treasury has been
seeking anyway to undercut by stealth the contributory principle. Industrial
disablement and death payments have been quietly dropped from the list of
contributory benefits. The Treasury would like to do the same with sick pay,
sickness benefit and invalidity benefit.
Other universal benefits have long been outside the National Insurance net
so are exempted from the constraints imposed by the contributory fiction.
But Mr Portillo has stressed he wants an open debate encompassing all
benefits. Fair enough, as long as he recognises he will only get one if the
government owns up about National Insurance contributions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
