<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Revenue hits out at DTI creditor plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue yesterday criticised proposals by the Department of Trade
and Industry that threaten its preferential status as a creditor to
companies in financial difficulties.
It argued that its priority ranking above other creditors was 'necessary',
and wanted it to be maintained in any changes to insolvency legislation.
The comments were in response to a DTI consultative document issued on
Tuesday which called for an overhaul of existing procedures for company
voluntary arrangements (CVAs) and administration orders. The document said
some countries were eliminating or reducing the number of preferential tax
creditors, and suggested that 'Crown preference' for pay-as-you-earn, value
added tax and other measures could be removed.
Banks yesterday maintained their tentative support for the proposals, which
would require them to lose some of their rights as priority creditors by
abiding by CVAs and giving a company seven days' notice before appointing
receivers.
One banker said he supported the principle of trying to rescue more
companies. 'We are not trigger happy,' he said. 'We have lost a lot of
customers and we want to stop losing them.'
But he questioned how far the proposals would succeed. 'So many of the
companies we see are bust by the time they suggest a CVA,' he said. 'They
are terminal cases and don't seek professional help in time.'
He also stressed the need for close supervision of a company's directors
once a CVA was under way to ensure that assets were not removed.
Consultation on the DTI document is open until until the end of January next
year.
Mr Tim Hayward, head of insolvency at KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy
firm, also welcomed the document. He stressed the need to balance the
concerns of directors in financial difficulties against the need to act
where there was no case for keeping an insolvent company operating.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
